{{Malay name|Anaqi Sufi|Omar Baki}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Anaqi Sufi Omar Baki | fullname = Pengiran Anaqi Sufi bin Pengiran Haji Omar Baki | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|7|22|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Brunei]] | height = | position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[Wijaya FC]] | clubnumber = 8 | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 2009–2011| caps1 = | goals1 =| clubs1 = [[AM Gunners]] | years2 = 2012–| caps2 = | goals2 =26| clubs2 = [[Wijaya FC]] | nationalyears1= 2012 | nationalcaps1= 0 | nationalgoals1= 0 | nationalteam1= [[Brunei national under-21 football team|Brunei U21]] | nationalyears2= 2015 | nationalcaps2= 2 | nationalgoals2= 0 | nationalteam2= [[Brunei national football team|Brunei]] | club-update = 25 October 2017 | ntupdate = 25 October 2017 }}
'''[[Malay styles and titles#Brunei|Pengiran]] Anaqi Sufi bin Pengiran Haji Omar Baki''' (born 22 July 1990) is a [[Brunei]]an [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Brunei Super League]] side [[Wijaya FC]] as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MS ABDB GO FIVE POINTS CLEAR AT THE TOP|url=https://www.brusports.com/2017/09/10/ms-abdb-go-five-points-clear-at-the-top/|date=10 September 2017|publisher=BruSports News|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> He has also played for the [[Brunei national football team]] on two occasions.
==Club career== A [[Direct free kick|free kick specialist]] by trade,<ref>{{cite web |title=31/07/2017 DST Super League|url=http://www.rtbnews.rtb.gov.bn/Lists/News/NewDispForm.aspx?ID=2702|date=31 July 2017|publisher=''[[Radio Television Brunei|Radio Televisyen Brunei]]''|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> Anaqi Sufi began his footballing career with [[AM Gunners]] of the [[Brunei Premier League]], the club that was headed by [[Prince Mateen of Brunei|Prince Abdul Mateen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brudirect.com:80/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Mar08/180308/nite31.htm|title=Charity Soccer Match|publisher=[[Borneo Bulletin]]|date=18 March 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422082606/http://brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Mar08/180308/nite31.htm|archivedate=2008-04-22|accessdate=25 October 2017|df=}}</ref> He scored the winner against [[Indera SC]] to send the Gunners to the semi-finals of the 2010 [[Brunei FA Cup|FA Cup]], only to be beaten by [[MS ABDB]] through a late winner by [[Safari Wahit]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FA Cup - MS ABDB shoot down the Gunners|url=http://bruneifootball.blogspot.com/2010/04/fa-cup-ms-abdb-shoot-down-gunners.html|date=11 April 2010|publisher=[[The Brunei Times]]|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>
Anaqi Sufi moved to [[Wijaya FC]] in 2012,<ref>{{cite web |title=Wijaya FC keep Lun Bawang planted|url=http://bruneifootball.blogspot.com/2012/01/wijaya-fc-keep-lun-bawang-planted.html|date=14 January 2012|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> and has been playing there since as an undisputed starter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coach lauds Wijaya’s best league performance|url=https://borneobulletin.com.bn/coach-lauds-wijayas-best-league-performance/|date=1 October 2017|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>
On 9 January 2018, Anaqi Sufi scored four goals in the [[Brunei FA Cup|DST FA Cup]] second round fixture against [[BSRC FT]], the fourth being a direct free-kick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wijaya FC berpesta gol atasi BSRC FT, 5 - 1|url=http://www.pelitabrunei.gov.bn/Lists/Berita%202018/NewDisplayForm.aspx?ID=12270|date=9 January 2018|publisher=Pelita Brunei|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>
==International career==
Anaqi Sufi was a squad member of the [[Brunei national under-21 football team|Brunei under-21 team]] that lifted the [[Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy]] in [[2012 Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy|2012]].<ref>{{cite web |title=HBT squad: Indonesia, Thailand, Malaysia are teams to watch|url=http://bruneifootball.blogspot.com/2010/04/fa-cup-ms-abdb-shoot-down-gunners.html|date=4 February 2012|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>
Anaqi Sufi was called up to the full [[Brunei national football team|Brunei squad]] in March 2015 for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC First Round|2018 World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Chinese Taipei national football team|Chinese Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://borneobulletin.com.bn/brunei-team-meet-chinese-taipei-named/|title=Brunei team to meet Chinese Taipei named|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|date=6 March 2015|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217224215/http://borneobulletin.com.bn/brunei-team-meet-chinese-taipei-named/|archivedate=17 February 2017|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> He made his international debut as a substitute in the second leg held in [[Bandar Seri Begawan]] where Brunei squandered their first leg away victory with a 0-2 defeat which eliminated them from the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=World Cup dreams over|url=http://bruneifootball.blogspot.com/2015/03/world-cup-dreams-over.html|date=18 March 2015|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> He made another appearance for the Wasps at a friendly against [[Singapore]] the following June.
==Personal life== Besides football, Anaqi Sufi has also represented Brunei in [[Brunei national futsal team|international futsal]] in [[2012 AFF Futsal Championship|2012]].<ref>{{cite web |title=AFF FUTSAL: Indonesia show serious contention; Laos hang on for win|url=http://www.aseanfootball.org/v2/2012/04/aff-futsal-2012-indonesia-show-serious-contention-laos-hang-on-for-win/|date=19 April 2012|publisher=[[ASEAN Football Federation]]|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref> His father, Pengiran Omar Baki Pengiran Japar, is a national chess exponent with a FIDE rating of 1780.<ref>{{cite web |title=Japar,Pg Omar Baki FIDE Chess Profile|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=10502149|date=|publisher=[[FIDE]]|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>
