{{Infobox stadium | name = The Showgrounds | nickname = | image = Newry Showground Panorama.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = The Showgrounds | fullname = | location = Greenbank Industrial Estate, Newry, [[County Down]], BT34 2QF | coordinates = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1923 | renovated = | expanded = 2010 | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = Grass (110 x 75 yds) | construction_cost = | architect = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = [[Newry City F.C.|Newry City FC]] (1923–2012) [[Newry City AFC]] (2013–Present) | capacity = 7,949 (limited to 2,275 – 1,080 seated).<ref name="niassembly1">[http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/qanda/2007mandate/writtenans/2010/101022.htm#3 Northern Ireland Assembly Answer to Written Question AQW1178/11] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030005751/http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/qanda/2007mandate/writtenans/2010/101022.htm#3 |date=30 October 2010 }}</ref> }}
'''The Showgrounds''' is a [[association football|football]] stadium in [[Newry]], [[County Down]], Northern Ireland. It was the home ground of [[Newry City F.C.]] and is now the home ground of their successor club, [[Newry City A.F.C.]]. The stadium holds 7,949, but is currently restricted to 2,275 under safety legislation.<ref name="niassembly1"/>
The stadium is located in the Greenbank Industrial Estate on the [[Warrenpoint]] Road, close to the [[Down GAA]] stadium [[Páirc Esler]].
== History == In 2009, The Showgrounds had two new stands constructed.<ref name=stand>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-20014360.html |title=Newry reveal forward thinking at Showgrounds |publisher=Belfast Telegraph (archived at Highbeam) |date= |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> In 2011, there were plans to turn The Showgrounds' pitch into an [[artificial turf]] pitch<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/local/cashstrapped-newry-embrace-amateur-future-28694900.html |title=Cash-strapped Newry embrace amateur future |publisher=Belfast Telegraph |date=22 December 2011 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> however due to Newry City's financial troubles, these plans were shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newrydemocrat.com/articles/sports/31009/newry-city-reboot-denied-league-of-ireland-access/ |title=Newry City reboot denied League of Ireland access |publisher=Newry Democrat |date= |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> In 2012, on the eighteenth day of the [[2012 Summer Olympics torch relay]], the Olympic torch passed The Showgrounds on its way to [[Páirc Esler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/torchrelay/day18 |title=Olympic Torch Relay – Londonderry to Newry |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>
In 2012, Newry City were liquidated after a [[Courts of Northern Ireland#Court of Judicature|High Court]] winding-up petition. Discussions on creating a [[Phoenix club (association football)|phoenix club]], initially titled "Newry City 2012" and eventually titled "Newry City AFC",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21759390 |title=Newry City AFC launch heralds new era |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 March 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> took place at The Showgrounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20595254 |title=Newry City poised to make comeback after being wound-up |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> When Newry City was wound up, The Showgrounds were not sold off with the club as it was owned by Newry City's supporters and not the club.<ref name=vid>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20244023 |title=What does future hold for football in Newry? |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> This meant that Newry City AFC would be able to use it as their home ground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.u.tv/Sport/Newry-launches-new-football-club/55c5e5cf-2400-445f-8f11-7601c6ae0953 |title=Newry launches new football club |publisher=UTV |date= |accessdate=4 January 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311154639/http://www.u.tv/Sport/Newry-launches-new-football-club/55c5e5cf-2400-445f-8f11-7601c6ae0953 |archivedate=11 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
== Usage == It was used to host Newry City's matches and also hosts the fixtures of Newry City AFC after Newry City was liquidated. It is also used for training.<ref name=vid /> In 2013, The Showgrounds were suggested as a temporary home ground for [[Warrenpoint Town F.C.|Warrenpoint Town]] after they were promoted to the [[NIFL Premiership]] as their Milltown Playing Field did not fulfill the criteria for use in the NIFL Premiership. However, the [[Irish Football Association]] blocked the move as the owners of The Showgrounds objected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/local/the-park/warrenpoint-towns-rise-to-premiership-football-is-almost-too-good-to-be-true-29261845.html |title=Warrenpoint Town's rise to Premiership football is almost too good to be true |publisher=Belfast Telegraph |date=13 May 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> Newry City AFC also gave reasons for objecting the potential groundshare, citing the poor quality of the playing surface, the lack of a licence for The Showgrounds to host NIFL Premiership matches and a large increase in insurance and running costs for Newry City if the groundshare went ahead.<ref>{{cite web|author=Category: Uncategorised |url=http://www.newry.ie/2-uncategorised/1662-newry-city-clarify-position-on-ground-sharing |title=Newry City clarify position on ground sharing |publisher=Newry.ie |date= |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>
The Showgrounds are also used to host the [[Bessbrook]] Cup Final, which is traditionally played on [[St. Stephen's Day]]. In 2013, the Bessbrook Cup final was postponed after one of The Showgrounds' floodlight pylons had been damaged in bad weather, which led to Health and Safety officials deeming that The Showgrounds were unsafe to be used for the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newrydemocrat.com/articles/sports/37672/boxing-day-cup-final-postponed/ |title=Boxing Day Cup Final Postponed |publisher=Newry Democrat |date=24 December 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>
== International football == The Showgrounds have been used to host youth international fixtures. In 2005, it was a venue in the [[2005 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/irish/4254839.stm |title=Catney called up for U19 tourney |publisher=BBC News |date=10 February 2005 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> In 2009, it was used to host some of the [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship qualification]] matches for Group 9.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/fixturesresults/round=15216/match=302205/index.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708102905/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/fixturesresults/round=15216/match=302205/index.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=8 July 2012 |title=UEFA European U-19 C'ship – Fixtures & Results |publisher=UEFA |date=13 October 2008 |accessdate=4 January 2014 }}</ref>
